Export Certificate from LIVE and Import to DR (IIS)
Objective

Copy an SSL certificate (including private key) from the LIVE server to the DR server and correctly bind it in IIS so each site uses the correct certificate.

PART 1 — EXPORT CERTIFICATE FROM LIVE SERVER
Step 1 — Open Certificate Manager
Press:
Win + R
Type:
mmc
Click:
File → Add/Remove Snap-in
Select:
Certificates → Add
Choose:
Computer account → Next → Local Computer → Finish
Click OK
Step 2 — Locate the Certificate

Navigate to:

Certificates (Local Computer)
→ Personal
→ Certificates

Find the certificate:

Issued To: jla
Step 3 — Export the Certificate
Right-click the certificate
Click:
All Tasks → Export
Step 4 — Export Settings
When prompted:

Private Key

✔ Yes, export the private key
File Format
✔ Personal Information Exchange (.PFX)
✔ Include all certificates in the certification path
☐ Delete the private key (IMPORTANT: leave unticked)
✔ Enable certificate privacy
Step 5 — Save File

Choose a location such as:

C:\Temp\jla.pfx
Step 6 — Set Password

Enter a password (you will need it on DR server).

Example:

TempPfx!2026
Step 7 — Complete Export

Click:

Finish

You should now have:

jla.pfx
PART 2 — COPY FILE TO DR SERVER

Copy:

jla.pfx

To DR server using:

RDP copy/paste
Network share

Place it in:

C:\Temp\
PART 3 — IMPORT CERTIFICATE ON DR SERVER
Step 1 — Open Certificate Manager

On DR server:

Win + R → certlm.msc
Step 2 — Navigate
Certificates (Local Computer)
→ Personal
→ Certificates
Step 3 — Import Certificate
Right-click:
Certificates
Click:
All Tasks → Import
Step 4 — Select File Type

Choose:

Personal Information Exchange (*.pfx)

Select:

jla.pfx
Step 5 — Enter Password

Enter the password set earlier.

Step 6 — Import Options
☐ Enable strong private key protection
✔ Mark this key as exportable
☐ Protect private key using virtualization
✔ Include all extended properties
Step 7 — Certificate Store

Select:

✔ Place all certificates in the following store
Certificate store: Personal
Step 8 — Finish Import

Click:

Finish
Step 9 — Verify Certificate

Open the certificate and confirm:

"You have a private key that corresponds to this certificate"
PART 4 — CONFIGURE IIS ON DR SERVER
Step 1 — Open IIS

Open:

Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager
Step 2 — Fix JLA Site Binding
Click:
Sites → JLA
Click:
Bindings…
Select:
https / jla / 443
Click:
Edit
Step 3 — Configure Binding

Set EXACTLY:

Type: https
IP Address: All Unassigned
Port: 443
Host name: jla
✔ Require Server Name Indication (IMPORTANT)
SSL certificate: jla
Step 4 — Handle Warning Message

If prompted:

"Another site is using the same HTTPS binding..."

Click:

NO

(We will configure each site separately.)

Step 5 — Fix Other Sites

Repeat for other sites (e.g. MailCheck):

Example:

Site: MailCheck
Host name: mailcheck
✔ Require Server Name Indication
SSL certificate: mailcheck
IMPORTANT RULE

Each site must have:

Unique hostname
Correct certificate
SNI enabled
PART 5 — VERIFY NO CONFLICTS

Open:

Sites → Bindings (global view)

Ensure:

No duplicate hostname on same port
PART 6 — TEST DR SERVER
Step 1 — Edit Hosts File (on your PC)

Add:

<DR-IP>    jla
Step 2 — Test

Open browser:

https://jla

Check:

No certificate warning
Correct site loads
PART 7 — CLEANUP

Delete the .pfx file from:

LIVE server
DR server
SUMMARY

You have now:

Exported certificate from LIVE ✔️
Imported to DR ✔️
Fixed IIS bindings ✔️
Enabled SNI ✔️
Ensured correct certificate per site ✔️

If needed, this setup supports full DR failover using DNS or load balancer.
